Fast Memory Without the Heap: Building a Stack Allocator in C++
The default new/delete operators are convenient, but they come with a cost. Every heap allocation involves a system call, internal book-keeping, and potential fragmentation. For performance-critical code like game engines, real-time systems, or tight inner loops, this overhead adds up fast. A stack allocator is one of the simplest tools to eliminate it.

The Core Idea
A stack allocator pre-allocates a large contiguous block of memory upfront and hands out chunks of it by simply advancing a pointer. There is no free list, no coalescing, no lock contention. 

Deallocation is equally trivial: you reset the pointer to a previously saved position, reclaiming everything allocated since that point in a single step.

class StackAllocator {
public:
  using Marker = std::size_t;

  // Will use a preallocated buffer of 1024*1024.
  StackAllocator() = default;

  // If you want to use your own preallocated buffer size.
  explicit StackAllocator(std::size_t capacity) :
      mBuffer(std::make_unique<std::byte[]>(capacity)),
      mCapacity(capacity),
      mOffset(0) {
        // empty
  }

  // No copying
  StackAllocator(const StackAllocator &) = delete;
  StackAllocator &operator(const StackAllocator &) = delete;

  void* allocate(std::size_t size, std::size_t alignment = alignof(std::max_align_t)) {
     std::size_t aligned = align_up(mOffset, alignment);
     if (aligned + size > mCapacity)
         return nullptr;
     mOffset = aligned + size;
     return mBuffer.get() + aligned;
 }

 Marker get_marker() const { 
     return mOffset; 
 }
 
 void free_to_marker(Marker marker) { 
     mOffset = marker; 
 }
 
 void reset() { 
     mOffset = 0; 
 }

private:
    static std::size_t align_up(std::size_t value, std::size_t alignment) {
        return (value + alignment - 1) & ~(alignment - 1);
    }

    std::unique_ptr<std::byte[]> mBuffer{};
    std::size_t mCapacity{1024*1024};
    std::size_t mOffset{0};
};
Using Markers for Scoped Lifetime
The marker system is what makes a stack allocator genuinely useful. Save a marker before a logical block of work, do all the allocations you need, then roll back to the marker when the work is done.

StackAllocator arena(1024 * 1024); // 1 MB arena
auto marker = arena.get_marker();

auto* vertices = static_cast<Vertex*>(arena.allocate(sizeof(Vertex) * 1000));
auto* indices = static_cast<uint32_t*>(arena.allocate(sizeof(uint32_t) * 3000));
process_mesh(vertices, indices);

arena.free_to_marker(marker); // reclaim both allocations instantly
This pattern maps naturally to frame-based work: reset the entire arena at the start of each frame and allocate freely throughout. No destructor calls, no fragmentation, no surprises.

Alignment Matters
One subtlety that trips up many implementations is alignment. CPUs require that types like float, int32_t, and SIMD vectors be placed at addresses that are multiples of their size. The align_up helper above
 uses a standard bitmask trick to round the current offset up to the nearest aligned boundary before each allocation. Without this, you get undefined behavior on most architectures and a performance penalty
 on the rest.

When to Reach for This Tool
A stack allocator shines when:

Allocations have a clear, nested lifetime (frame data during rendering, request-scoped buffers, parse trees).
You know an upper bound on memory usage upfront or your memory is limited.
You want deterministic allocation time with zero fragmentation.
Allocations are forbitten because of approal-related requirements like an embedded device for functional-safety.
It falls flat when objects have independent lifetimes that cannot be ordered. For that, a pool allocator or a more general arena is a better fit. We will handle this in another blog post.

Takeaways
A stack allocator is perhaps 50 lines of code, yet it can replace thousands of heap allocations per second with pointer arithmetic. It is one of the clearest examples of a domain constraint — “these things
 all die together” — being turned directly into a performance advantage. If your profiler is pointing at memory allocation, this is the first place to look.
